SIMPLE: sheathe
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sheathe
<hw>Sheathe</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Sheathed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Sheating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Written also
<ets>sheath</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To put into a sheath, case,
or scabbard; to inclose or cover with, or as with, a sheath or
case.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The leopard . . . keeps the claws of his fore feet turned up from
the ground, and <qex>sheathed</qex> in the skin of his toes.</q>
<rj><qau>Grew.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>'T is in my breast she <qex>sheathes</qex> her dagger now.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To fit or furnish, as with a sheath.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To case or cover with something which protects, as
thin boards, sheets of metal, and the like; <as>as, to <ex>sheathe</ex>
a ship with copper</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To obtund or blunt, as acrimonious substances, or
sharp particles.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Arbuthnot.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To sheathe the sword</b></col>, <cd>to make
peace.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sheathed</ent>⟦br⟧
